warnings.title: Executable Failed Integrity Check
warnings.description: The sample executable has failed to match the internal checksum stored in it. This might indicate that the executable is corrupt and may not run. You may want to validate in the video if the executable ran.

iocs.description: Adware is software which automatically renders advertisements in order to generate revenue for its author. The advertisements may be in the user interface of the software or on a screen presented to the user during the installation process. The functions may be designed to analyze which Internet sites the user visits and to present advertising pertinent to the types of goods or services featured there.
iocs.title: Artifact Flagged as Known Adware by Antivirus

iocs.description: An antivirus engine flagged an artifact as potentially malicious. This may be a false positive as antivirus programs will also flag packed or encrypted software with a signature. Please confirm the file is indeed malicious. Checking other indicators and outbound communications will help to confirm this.
iocs.title: Artifact Flagged by Antivirus

iocs.description: An executable artifact has encrypted section(s). This usually indicates that the author is attempting to hide or obfuscate code or data.
iocs.title: Executable with Encrypted Sections

iocs.description: The IsDebuggerPresent function can be used by a process to check if a debugger has been attached to it, or is currently active on the system.  Malware authors often check for the presence of a debugger as this is an indication that the malware is being analysed. The Malware may not run, or it may function differently, if a debugger is present, to make it more difficult to reverse-engineer its behavior. This is not an indicator of malicious activity as often legitimate programs import this function.
iocs.title: Executable Imported the IsDebuggerPresent Symbol

iocs.description: Some malware applications write code into areas of memory intended for data (such as a thread's stack) and then the application executes the malicious code. Windows introduced Data Execution Prevention (DEP) which proveded protection against this type of attack. If an attempt to execute code is made in a page that does not have the PAGE_EXECUTE_ protection, an access violation will occur. Malware will often allocate memory in which it will inject code. In order to bypass DEP the allocated memory must be marked Read, Write and Execute. The submitted sample allocated a memory region with the flag PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE. This could indicate the presence of code injection, into itself or a remote process.
iocs.title: Potential Code Injection Detected

iocs.description: Malware will modify executables on a system, to hide logs or other evidence. Also, by modifying various executables it can disable functionality in the system which may detect or hamper the operation of the malware. Lastly, it may be attempting to hide an executable, so that it appears to be a legitimate file. Please review the 'Disk Artifacts' section in order to view additional details about this file.
iocs.title: Process Modified an Executable File

iocs.description: Authenticode is Microsoft's solution to ensuring integrity of software introduced to the operating system. Authenticode only assures users that the publisher is participating in the trusted entities infrastructure and that the binary has not been altered, the presence of a certificate does not guarantee that the signed code is safe to execute. Starting with Windows Vista, Microsoft required that all driver code contain a digital signature.
iocs.title: Executable Signed With Digital Certificate

iocs.description: Malware will often create a new executable file in a user directory such as 'Local Settings' or 'Application Data' in an attempt to hide its presence on the system. Often the name of the file is similar to the name of common system or user files. This is done to hide the executable, as the user may believe it's a legitimate file. Please review the 'Disk Artifacts' section in order to view additional details about this file.
iocs.title: Process Created an Executable in a User Directory

iocs.description: In Windows, resources are read-only data embedded in EXE and DLL files. Resources usually consist of Bitmaps, Icon & Cursor data. However, Microsoft also allows for files such as executables, PDFs and HTML to be embedded. Malware will often utilize the Resource section to host executables in both encrypted and unencrypted forms. These Executables vary and can be part of the trojan or simply a secondary utility, even a genuine Microsoft utility such as Browstat.exe
iocs.title: Executable Has Embedded Executable in Resources

iocs.description: A process registered a service DLL using Regsvr32.exe. Malware will often download additional DLLs to provide enhanced functionality. These DLLs will be registered and their path with often be added to various autorun or other registry keys used to maintain persistence on a system.
iocs.title: Process Registered a Service DLL

iocs.description: An antivirus service flagged an artifact as malicious. When using antivirus software, relying on a single engine is susceptible to false-positives. Online services, such as VirusTotal and Reversing Labs, use multiple antivirus engines to scan a file and the scan results of all engines are taken together to make a more accurate determination. One or more of these services have indicated that the file is malicious with a high degree of confidence. The results of individual antivirus engine scans are displayed, if available.
iocs.title: Artifact Flagged Malicious by Antivirus Service

iocs.description: File extensions are a primary means of identifying a file's type. Windows uses a number of standard file extensions to identify executable files. Common executable extensions include '.exe', and '.dll', but there are quite a few others. Malware authors will often alter an executable file's extension when creating the file on disk in an effort to obscure the file type.
iocs.title: Executable Artifact has Misleading File Extension

iocs.description: Thread Local Storage (TLS) is a Windows storage class in which a data object is not an automatic stack variable, yet is local to each thread that runs the code. When TLS is implemented by an executable, the code will typically contain a .tls section in the PE header. TLS supports callback functions for initialization and termination of TLS data objects. Windows executes these functions before running code at the normal start of a program. TLS callback functions allow malware authors to execute malicious code before the debugger has a chance to pause at the traditional entry point. This allows malware to infect the system or disable the debugger before the analyst has a chance to look at the sample's code.
iocs.title: PE Contains TLS Callback Entries

iocs.description: Malware will modify files in user directories to hide logs or other evidence. Also, by modifying various files it can disable functionality in the system which may detect or hamper the operation of the malware. Lastly, it may be attempting to hide an executable, so that it appears to be a legitimate file. Please review the 'Disk Artifacts' section in order to view additional details about this file.
iocs.title: Process Modified File in a User Directory

iocs.description: A COM class has a few subkeys of particular interest to a packager and his associated support teams. One of these attributes in particular is: InProcServer32. The InProcServer32 key contains the path to the actual DLL itself, or can also contain a Windows Installer Darwin Descriptor. When an application or script uses an API call such as "CreateObject", The operating system will first lookup the ProgID in the Windows registry, it will then cross reference the ProgID with its associated ClassID which will in turn look for an InProcServer32 value which will contain the path to the actual DLL which contains the COM class.
iocs.title: Process Registered COM Server DLL

iocs.description: An antivirus engine flagged a digitally signed artifact as a Trojan. A Trojan is a program that gains privileged access to the operating system while appearing to perform a desirable function but instead drops a malicious payload, often a backdoor allowing unauthorized access to the system. Trojans may steal information or infect the host systems. They are commonly installed by drive-by downloads or embedded into games or Internet driven applications. In general, digitally signed software should be safer to use than unsigned software, since the creator of the software can be verified. However, Adware and other potentially unwanted applications are increasingly leveraging digital signatures to appear legitimate. In addition, if a malware author can steal a signing key, malware signed with the stolen key cannot be distinguished from legitimately signed software by the digital signature alone.
iocs.title: Signed Artifact Flagged as Known Trojan by Antivirus

iocs.description: An executable file contains a library reference to the SetWindowsHookEx function.  This library could be used to monitor keyboard or other input, which could indicate the presence of a keylogger or other spyware.
iocs.title: Hook Procedure Detected in Executable

iocs.description: A PE file was found with an invalid checksum. The PE Optional Header contains a field that holds a checksum. This is generated when the PE is built and should be static across the life of the executable. Malware may modify the executable, but many do not repair the checksum to account for permanent changes.
iocs.title: PE Checksum is Invalid
